00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:04,000
Downloaded From www.AllSubs.org

1
00:00:20,807 --> 00:00:23,685
(# Moonlight Serenade)

2
00:01:48,367 --> 00:01:50,642
Hello, Mr Kranz.

3
00:01:50,687 --> 00:01:53,759
- I'd like to redeem my...
- I know! The trombone.

4
00:01:53,807 --> 00:01:56,162
I always keep her hanging in the window

5
00:01:56,207 --> 00:01:59,517
so when you walk by
you can see she is still there.

6
00:01:59,567 --> 00:02:01,125
I keep my eyes on her.

7
00:02:01,167 --> 00:02:04,398
Say, Mr Miller,
where'd you got the money this time?

8
00:02:04,447 --> 00:02:08,679
- Working in a gas station.
- And now you've got another band job?

9
00:02:08,727 --> 00:02:13,323
Yep. I'm with Minton at the Sunset Hotel.
Chummy's gonna pick me up.

10
00:02:13,367 --> 00:02:16,803
Your friend Chummy,
why don't he hock something?

11
00:02:16,847 --> 00:02:19,122
- He plays the piano.
- I see!

12
00:02:19,167 --> 00:02:24,321
That's all we need! To schlep a piano
in and out every once in a while.

13
00:02:24,367 --> 00:02:27,723
That string of pearls,
how much did you say that was?

14
00:02:27,767 --> 00:02:30,156
I'd like to give my girl a birthday present.

15
00:02:30,207 --> 00:02:32,163
Isn't it wonderful to be young?

16
00:02:32,207 --> 00:02:37,281
He just got his trombone out of hock
and he wants to buy a $100 necklace.

17
00:02:37,327 --> 00:02:39,045
$100?

18
00:02:39,087 --> 00:02:42,079
I'd like to give her this.
Haven't seen her for a few years.

19
00:02:42,127 --> 00:02:44,925
- You are engaged?
- No, not exactly.

20
00:02:44,967 --> 00:02:49,199
We went around together when we were
in college. University of Colorado.

21
00:02:49,247 --> 00:02:52,125
$100. That's a lot of money, isn't it?

22
00:02:52,167 --> 00:02:55,239
For a regular customer,
I make a special price.

23
00:02:55,287 --> 00:02:58,279
- (Car horn)
- I guess that's Chummy.

24
00:02:59,047 --> 00:03:01,038
A hundred dollars.

25
00:03:03,607 --> 00:03:05,598
Here's for the horn.

26
00:03:05,647 --> 00:03:08,605
- Thanks. Goodbye.
- Goodbye, Mr Miller.

27
00:03:12,367 --> 00:03:16,406
- Where'd you get this one, Chummy?
- Made a deal on my Briscoe.

28
00:03:16,447 --> 00:03:19,723
She's a beaut.
45 horsepower. Only four years old.

29
00:03:19,767 --> 00:03:23,362
- 45 horse...
- Come on, hop in. We gotta get goin'.

30
00:03:24,647 --> 00:03:27,400
- Isn't this a darb, kid?
- Yeah, gee whiz!

31
00:03:27,447 --> 00:03:30,484
- You bring my arrangement?
- You're sittin' on it.

32
00:03:30,527 --> 00:03:34,236
But this is the Sunset Hotel,
potted palms and marble stairs.

33
00:03:34,287 --> 00:03:37,040
- Minton's band plays sweet.
- I know that.

34
00:03:37,087 --> 00:03:40,636
Don't try to slip in
that arrangement of yours tonight.

35
00:03:40,687 --> 00:03:44,521
- We don't wanna lose this job.
- Stop worryin'. This is a classic.

36
00:03:44,567 --> 00:03:47,798
I Dreamt I Dwelt In Marble Halls,
it's a classic!

37
00:03:47,847 --> 00:03:52,841
When Minton hears this arrangement,
he'll give us a job for life. Let's go.

38
00:03:59,687 --> 00:04:02,565
(# Upbeat swing)

39
00:04:21,807 --> 00:04:23,923
(# Romantic swing)

40
00:04:39,567 --> 00:04:43,606
Too bad you can't keep the trombone
and hock the arrangement.

41
00:04:52,167 --> 00:04:54,635
- You know where there's Venice?
- Italy.

42
00:04:54,687 --> 00:04:58,123
No! Venice here.
By the pier, with that big wheel.

43
00:04:58,167 --> 00:05:01,443
- Oh, yeah.
- You boys go out there next Monday.

44
00:05:01,487 --> 00:05:04,843
- This fellow Pollack, he has tryouts.
- Ben Pollack?

45
00:05:04,887 --> 00:05:08,402
Ben Pollack. He gets together a new band.

46
00:05:08,447 --> 00:05:10,563
They go for a long, long trip.

47
00:05:10,607 --> 00:05:13,565
- How do you know?
- A fellow told me this morning.

48
00:05:13,607 --> 00:05:16,326
- You boys go out there.
- Sure. Thanks a lot.

49
00:05:16,367 --> 00:05:17,686
Next Monday?

50
00:05:17,727 --> 00:05:20,195
That gives you a week
to get your trombone out.

51
00:05:20,247 --> 00:05:23,080
- You could work in a gas station.
- Not me.

52
00:05:23,127 --> 00:05:25,163
I'm gonna work on arrangements.

53
00:05:25,207 --> 00:05:29,120
For me, I'm glad for your business,
Mr Miller,

54
00:05:29,167 --> 00:05:33,445
but why don't you give up this arranging
and stick with the trombone?

55
00:05:33,487 --> 00:05:36,524
That's a good question.
I wish I knew the answer.

56
00:05:36,567 --> 00:05:40,321
But I have one idea up here in my head.

57
00:05:40,367 --> 00:05:43,723
To me, music is more
than just one instrument.

58
00:05:43,767 --> 00:05:46,520
It's a whole orchestra playing together. See?

59
00:05:46,567 --> 00:05:50,355
The only way I can express myself
is to work out an arrangement.

60
00:05:50,407 --> 00:05:53,126
See? Thanks for the tip.

61
00:05:53,167 --> 00:05:55,362
Come on.

62
00:05:55,407 --> 00:05:57,637
(# Ragtime piano)

63
00:06:46,527 --> 00:06:48,483
Great!

64
00:06:48,527 --> 00:06:51,724
- Thanks, Ben.
- You're in. You're in.

65
00:06:51,767 --> 00:06:53,758
- Who's next?
- I am.

66
00:06:54,767 --> 00:06:56,883
I've done some arrangements...

67
00:06:56,927 --> 00:06:59,646
I'm full up on arrangements.
I need more musicians.

68
00:06:59,687 --> 00:07:03,282
I've been working on 'em all week.
They're in your style.

69
00:07:03,327 --> 00:07:07,081
I appreciate that. Lay them on the piano,
I'll try 'em some other time.

70
00:07:07,127 --> 00:07:08,958
Uh-huh.

71
00:07:09,967 --> 00:07:13,277
- My name's on the cover.
- Swell.

72
00:07:13,327 --> 00:07:14,965
OK, who's next?

73
00:07:15,007 --> 00:07:18,124
I am. My name's Schwartz.
Wilbur Schwartz.

74
00:07:18,167 --> 00:07:21,716
Clarinet, eh? Sit down at the first chair
and blow a little bit.

75
00:07:21,767 --> 00:07:26,318
- What tune do you want me to play?
- Do you read at sight?

76
00:07:26,367 --> 00:07:29,484
- Try me.
- Chummy, get him something to read.

77
00:07:45,487 --> 00:07:47,478
One, two.

78
00:07:47,527 --> 00:07:49,518
(# Plays upbeat tune)

79
00:08:18,887 --> 00:08:20,878
(Music stops)

80
00:08:31,847 --> 00:08:35,806
Hey, Glenn! Come on back.
Mr Pollack wants to talk to you.

81
00:08:35,847 --> 00:08:39,726
He says your arrangement is a pip!
Your arrangement!

82
00:08:41,047 --> 00:08:43,720
I'm playing in the band
and working on arrangements.

83
00:08:43,767 --> 00:08:45,439
I got a two-week advance.

84
00:08:45,487 --> 00:08:47,478
You are a regular Rockefeller!

85
00:08:47,527 --> 00:08:51,884
- I want to thank you for everything.
- Don't mention about it.

86
00:08:51,927 --> 00:08:54,805
I'm only glad it worked so good out.

87
00:08:54,847 --> 00:08:57,998
About that string of pearls
for my girl's birthday.

88
00:08:58,047 --> 00:09:02,199
You said something
about a special price for those.

89
00:09:02,247 --> 00:09:06,877
For you it's $80.
You pay me 40 down and $5 a week.

90
00:09:06,927 --> 00:09:09,236
- Good enough.
- Shall I mail it for you?

91
00:09:09,287 --> 00:09:12,245
I better take 'em with me.
I'm not sure of her address.

92
00:09:12,287 --> 00:09:15,518
We're booked into Denver.
She lives right near there.

93
00:09:15,567 --> 00:09:18,604
Ten, 20, 30, 40.
There's the 40.

94
00:09:18,647 --> 00:09:22,765
- And here is for the trombone.
- All right.

95
00:09:22,807 --> 00:09:26,243
- Thank you very much.
- Same to you, and good luck.

96
00:09:26,287 --> 00:09:29,165
I hope you stay out
of pawnshops for a while.

97
00:09:29,207 --> 00:09:32,404
- So do I! Goodbye.
- Goodbye, Mr Miller.

98
00:09:40,967 --> 00:09:43,162
- Glenn, come on!
- A Pierce-Arrow?

99
00:09:43,207 --> 00:09:46,085
Yeah! I got it for the old car and 100 bucks.

100
00:09:46,127 --> 00:09:49,085
Much heavier.
It'll hold the road better on a long trip.

101
00:09:49,127 --> 00:09:52,164
If the band folds up,
we can sell it to an undertaker.

102
00:09:52,207 --> 00:09:55,085
Get in the back, I'll give you a ride in style.

103
00:10:14,447 --> 00:10:17,519
Hurry, Glenn. We're due
at the Denver Palace in ten minutes.

104
00:10:17,567 --> 00:10:20,286
- How much, sir?
- Oh, give us five.

105
00:10:32,607 --> 00:10:35,440
Hello. I want Boulder 6-1-7-0.

106
00:10:37,527 --> 00:10:39,518
How many?

107
00:10:45,447 --> 00:10:47,438
(Telephone)

108
00:10:48,327 --> 00:10:50,238
I'll get it, Mother.

109
00:10:54,287 --> 00:10:55,561
Hello?

110
00:10:55,607 --> 00:10:58,599
Hello? Helen? How's my girl?

111
00:10:59,407 --> 00:11:01,363
Your girl? Who is this?

112
00:11:01,407 --> 00:11:03,682
Who is this? Is this Helen Burger?

113
00:11:03,727 --> 00:11:05,365
Yes, but there must be some...

114
00:11:05,407 --> 00:11:09,366
- Well, it's Glenn!
- Glenn? Glenn who?

115
00:11:10,327 --> 00:11:12,045
It's Glenn Miller!

116
00:11:12,087 --> 00:11:14,442
Glenn Miller?

117
00:11:14,487 --> 00:11:16,762
Oh, Glenn Miller.

118
00:11:16,807 --> 00:11:20,436
Well, now, honestly.
After two years and not a word.

119
00:11:20,487 --> 00:11:22,125
Didn't you get my card?

120
00:11:22,167 --> 00:11:24,317
The one you wrote
a year ago last Christmas?

121
00:11:24,367 --> 00:11:26,756
Well, I haven't heard from you either.

122
00:11:26,807 --> 00:11:31,119
I didn't know where you were.
I don't even know where you are now.

123
00:11:31,167 --> 00:11:35,365
I'm down here in Denver.
I want to see you. How about tonight?

124
00:11:35,407 --> 00:11:37,557
Oh, I'm sorry. I have a date.

125
00:11:37,607 --> 00:11:41,122
Couldn't you break it?
I'm with Pollack and we're leavin' tomorrow.

126
00:11:41,167 --> 00:11:42,964
Now, honestly, I...

127
00:11:43,007 --> 00:11:45,726
(Chummy) Glenn, come on, hurry it up.

128
00:11:45,767 --> 00:11:48,964
I'll see you later, then.
Gee, there's a lot I want to tell you.

129
00:11:49,007 --> 00:11:53,558
- Glenn, wait a minute...
- I'll be out right after I finish work. Bye.

130
00:11:54,647 --> 00:11:56,638
Glenn? Hello?

131
00:11:59,687 --> 00:12:01,757
Well, honestly.

132
00:12:08,447 --> 00:12:11,439
- Hi, Dad.
- Going out, Helen?

133
00:12:11,487 --> 00:12:14,365
This is a new wrinkle, isn't it?
Ed keeping you waiting.

134
00:12:14,407 --> 00:12:17,399
It isn't Ed tonight.
It's a man I haven't seen for years.

135
00:12:17,447 --> 00:12:19,483
Not Ed? What's happened?

136
00:12:19,527 --> 00:12:21,995
It must be serious for you
to break a date with Ed.

137
00:12:22,047 --> 00:12:24,766
No, Mother. Glenn isn't my type.

138
00:12:24,807 --> 00:12:28,959
I guess I'm just too practical
or unromantic or something.

139
00:12:29,007 --> 00:12:35,082
I want a man like Ed who's got a factory
or a store or something solid.

140
00:12:35,127 --> 00:12:38,403
I certainly don't want
a wandering nomad like Glenn Miller.

141
00:12:38,447 --> 00:12:40,802
What's he do, this Glenn Miller?

142
00:12:41,447 --> 00:12:45,122
I don't really know except he said
he was in Denver for overnight.

143
00:12:45,167 --> 00:12:47,237
He's gonna pick me up after work.

144
00:12:47,287 --> 00:12:51,758
He must be a hard worker.
It's nearly 9:00 now.

145
00:12:51,807 --> 00:12:54,480
It is?

146
00:12:54,527 --> 00:12:56,518
Well.

147
00:13:02,327 --> 00:13:04,761
(Clock strikes)

148
00:13:04,807 --> 00:13:07,924
Oh! There's really no excuse for this!

149
00:13:07,967 --> 00:13:09,958
The least he could've done was phone.

150
00:13:10,007 --> 00:13:12,567
- Unless he was in an accident.
- Call him.

151
00:13:12,607 --> 00:13:14,598
How can I? I don't know where he is.

152
00:13:14,647 --> 00:13:17,605
If I'm going hunting in the morning,
I've gotta get to bed.

153
00:13:17,647 --> 00:13:20,161
Sam's picking me up at the crack of dawn.

154
00:13:20,247 --> 00:13:23,762
- Doesn't look as if he's coming tonight.
- It certainly doesn't!

155
00:13:23,807 --> 00:13:26,002
Even if he did come, I wouldn't see him.

156
00:13:26,047 --> 00:13:28,242
Then we can all go to bed?

157
00:13:28,287 --> 00:13:32,041
Well, so much for Mr Glenn Miller.

158
00:13:32,087 --> 00:13:34,078
I'll never see him again.

159
00:13:48,247 --> 00:13:50,238
(Glenn, calling softly) Helen?

160
00:13:51,607 --> 00:13:54,246
Helen?

161
00:13:54,287 --> 00:13:56,437
(Whistles)

162
00:13:57,767 --> 00:13:59,086
Helen?

163
00:14:05,047 --> 00:14:06,605
Helen!

164
00:14:06,647 --> 00:14:09,207
(Whistles)

165
00:14:09,247 --> 00:14:11,966
Helen! (Whistles)

166
00:14:15,567 --> 00:14:18,365
- Oh, there you are.
- Glenn Miller, you go away.

167
00:14:19,047 --> 00:14:22,437
I don't want to go away.
I came to see you. We have a date.

168
00:14:22,487 --> 00:14:27,322
- Shh! You'll wake up the neighbourhood.
- How can I talk to you?

169
00:14:28,687 --> 00:14:30,917
You keep quiet. I'll be right down.

170
00:14:51,767 --> 00:14:53,246
Hello, Helen.

171
00:14:53,287 --> 00:14:55,847
What's the matter with you,
coming at this hour?

172
00:14:55,887 --> 00:14:59,675
I told you I'd come out after work.
I got here as quick as I could.

173
00:14:59,727 --> 00:15:03,686
- Shh. Be quiet.
- You haven't changed a bit, have you?

174
00:15:03,727 --> 00:15:07,356
Just as feisty as ever, and just as pretty too.

175
00:15:07,407 --> 00:15:11,685
I must be pretty! Wearing this kimono
and my hair up in curlers.

176
00:15:11,727 --> 00:15:14,002
Is that what they are? Come on, sit down.

177
00:15:14,047 --> 00:15:17,483
- It's cold out here.
- Come on. It's a beautiful night.

178
00:15:17,527 --> 00:15:18,755
Gee.

179
00:15:18,807 --> 00:15:23,198
There. I bought you a present
for your birthday.

180
00:15:23,247 --> 00:15:26,876
My birthday?
That isn't until next November.

181
00:15:26,927 --> 00:15:28,918
This is for your last birthday.

182
00:15:31,927 --> 00:15:35,522
Why, they're beautiful!
But I can't accept a present like this.

183
00:15:35,567 --> 00:15:38,798
Why not? They're not real.
I wish they were.

184
00:15:38,847 --> 00:15:43,045
I got 'em out in Los Angeles in a pa...
In a, uh... A, uh...

185
00:15:43,087 --> 00:15:45,476
I'll get you some real ones someday.

186
00:15:46,567 --> 00:15:47,966
Honestly.

187
00:15:48,007 --> 00:15:51,682
Two years and not a word
and then a present like this.

188
00:15:51,727 --> 00:15:56,403
You know, with some people
you don't have to write. You just know.

189
00:15:56,447 --> 00:15:59,564
- I knew you'd be here.
- Oh, you did?

190
00:15:59,607 --> 00:16:02,758
Sure. I knew you'd be just the same.

191
00:16:02,807 --> 00:16:05,799
Just sitting around waiting
for you to show up, I suppose?

192
00:16:05,847 --> 00:16:09,522
"How is my girl?" you said.
Well, you happen to be wrong!

193
00:16:09,567 --> 00:16:12,525
I've been engaged to Ed Healey
for nearly a year.

194
00:16:12,567 --> 00:16:15,877
Did it occur to you that I might not care
if I ever saw you again?

195
00:16:15,927 --> 00:16:17,997
No, it never did.

196
00:16:18,047 --> 00:16:19,958
Never.

197
00:16:20,007 --> 00:16:23,079
- Never.
- Why can't I ever stay mad at you?

198
00:16:23,127 --> 00:16:25,766
You had me worried there for a minute.

199
00:16:25,807 --> 00:16:28,082
Honestly!

200
00:16:28,127 --> 00:16:32,678
If you were anybody else,
I would never speak to you again.

201
00:16:32,727 --> 00:16:37,118
Look at me. Sitting here
in this kimono and my hair all...

202
00:16:37,167 --> 00:16:39,727
- Those curlers.
- Terrible, isn't it?

203
00:16:41,167 --> 00:16:44,762
Helen, now look, I've got an idea.

204
00:16:44,807 --> 00:16:48,561
Come with me to Fort Morgan.
I'm gonna introduce you to my folks.

205
00:16:49,167 --> 00:16:51,203
- Now?
- Right now.

206
00:16:51,247 --> 00:16:53,681
People do sleep between 3am and 6am.

207
00:16:53,727 --> 00:16:56,116
They'll be crazy about you.

208
00:16:56,167 --> 00:16:59,125
- And they'll give us breakfast.
- How do we get there?

209
00:16:59,167 --> 00:17:01,601
- I'll get a taxi.
- A taxi to Fort Morgan?

210
00:17:01,647 --> 00:17:03,842
- Sure.
- That's so extravagant.

211
00:17:03,887 --> 00:17:06,481
- It isn't far.
- Maybe I can get the family car.

212
00:17:06,527 --> 00:17:08,518
Wonderful. Wait a minute.

213
00:17:08,567 --> 00:17:10,683
Let me try these on for size, hm?

214
00:17:12,007 --> 00:17:12,996
There.

215
00:17:13,047 --> 00:17:15,083
(Door opening)

216
00:17:16,607 --> 00:17:17,756
Uh-oh.

217
00:17:17,807 --> 00:17:20,275
- Mr Burger, I...
- Take it easy, son.

218
00:17:20,327 --> 00:17:23,160
I'm just going hunting, for jackrabbits.

219
00:17:39,647 --> 00:17:42,115
- Glenn!
- It's Glenn!

220
00:17:42,167 --> 00:17:45,557
Hi, Herb. How are you?
Glad to see you. Hello, Irene.

221
00:17:45,607 --> 00:17:48,519
- What a surprise! I had no idea.
- Hello, Mother.

222
00:17:48,567 --> 00:17:50,558
Glad to see you. Mother, this is...

223
00:17:50,607 --> 00:17:53,246
You don't need to tell me. You're Helen!

224
00:17:53,287 --> 00:17:55,721
We've been hearing about you for years.

225
00:17:55,767 --> 00:17:58,076
Why, yes. I'm very happy to meet you.

226
00:17:58,127 --> 00:18:01,119
- Daddy'll be down in a minute.
- Dean and Velna?

227
00:18:01,167 --> 00:18:03,806
They're fine! I'll show you
a picture of the baby.

228
00:18:03,847 --> 00:18:06,680
- Sure.
- She your girl, Glenn?

229
00:18:06,727 --> 00:18:08,399
That's right, Herb.

230
00:18:08,447 --> 00:18:10,597
Are you and Glenn gonna get married?

231
00:18:10,647 --> 00:18:13,798
Don't ask that!
We just take such things for granted.

232
00:18:13,847 --> 00:18:15,917
- How are you, son?
- Fine.

233
00:18:15,967 --> 00:18:19,004
- And you're Helen. Welcome to the family.
- Thank you.

234
00:18:19,047 --> 00:18:22,881
- You gonna get these kids some breakfast?
- I certainly am!

235
00:18:22,927 --> 00:18:26,681
You might've let us know where you are
and what your plans are.

236
00:18:26,727 --> 00:18:29,685
We have to ask Helen, eh?
I'll bet he tells you everything.

237
00:18:29,727 --> 00:18:33,003
Oh, no, Mr Miller.
I seem to be the last person he tells.

238
00:18:33,047 --> 00:18:35,641
- Yeah.
- Well, come on.

239
00:18:35,687 --> 00:18:37,723
- You like hotcakes, Helen?
- Yes.

240
00:18:37,767 --> 00:18:39,564
Mom makes pretty good ones...

241
00:18:40,367 --> 00:18:41,846
(Men) # Little brown jug, how I love thee

242
00:18:41,887 --> 00:18:44,276
# Ha-ha-ha, you and me

243
00:18:44,327 --> 00:18:48,764
# Little brown jug, how I love thee... #

244
00:18:51,607 --> 00:18:54,360
Good old Colorado U.
It hasn't changed a bit.

245
00:18:54,407 --> 00:18:56,875
No, it's just as pretty as ever.

246
00:18:56,927 --> 00:19:00,602
We still have time. Let's walk
across the campus for old times' sake.

247
00:19:00,647 --> 00:19:02,638
- I'd love to.
- Come on.

248
00:19:04,567 --> 00:19:07,718
- Wish I didn't have to leave so soon.
- I do too.

249
00:19:08,847 --> 00:19:11,361
Listen. It's the Glee Club rehearsing.

250
00:19:12,447 --> 00:19:15,484
- I love that song.
- What, Little Brown Jug?

251
00:19:15,527 --> 00:19:18,200
That's sort of a tin-eared tune.

252
00:19:18,247 --> 00:19:20,636
Why, that's one of my favourites.

253
00:19:20,687 --> 00:19:24,726
My dad used to sing it to me
when I was a little girl. I guess that's why.

254
00:19:24,767 --> 00:19:27,076
- They sing it pretty well.
- Mm-hm.

255
00:19:28,607 --> 00:19:31,644
When something's
really wonderful like that, I know it.

256
00:19:31,687 --> 00:19:35,043
I get kind of a funny feeling
up the back of my neck.

257
00:19:35,087 --> 00:19:38,762
That's how I can tell.
Sort of makes my hair stand on end.

258
00:19:38,807 --> 00:19:41,037
- Is that so?
- Yeah.

259
00:19:41,087 --> 00:19:43,521
Looks pretty normal from here.

260
00:19:43,567 --> 00:19:45,558
It just feels that way!

261
00:19:46,367 --> 00:19:48,722
- Remember that lake?
- Yes, I do.

262
00:19:53,327 --> 00:19:55,966
- Where do you go from here?
- We're heading east.

263
00:19:56,007 --> 00:19:59,283
Chicago, New York.
We're booked into the Club Fifty there.

264
00:19:59,327 --> 00:20:01,158
- Ever been to New York?
- No.

265
00:20:01,207 --> 00:20:03,562
Neither have I. I hear it's quite a town.

266
00:20:03,607 --> 00:20:06,360
You're certainly seeing America, aren't you?

267
00:20:07,367 --> 00:20:09,642
You think I'm kinda rudderless, don't you?

268
00:20:09,687 --> 00:20:12,679
Wandering over the country with the band.

269
00:20:12,727 --> 00:20:15,480
- Yes, I guess I do.
- But I'm not, though.

270
00:20:15,527 --> 00:20:20,521
I know exactly where I'm going.
I know exactly what I want to do.

271
00:20:20,567 --> 00:20:21,966
You do?

272
00:20:22,007 --> 00:20:25,682
I'm not gonna be a sideman all my life,
a trombone player.

273
00:20:25,727 --> 00:20:28,036
I'm gonna have a band all of my own.

274
00:20:28,087 --> 00:20:30,920
I'm gonna play my own kind of music.

275
00:20:30,967 --> 00:20:35,199
I... It's hard to explain, but a band...

276
00:20:35,247 --> 00:20:39,684
A band oughta have a sound all of its own,
oughta have a personality.

277
00:20:40,607 --> 00:20:43,167
- Sort of like a person.
- Uh-huh.

278
00:20:43,207 --> 00:20:45,596
How do you get this different sound?

279
00:20:45,647 --> 00:20:48,161
You see, the arrangements,

280
00:20:48,207 --> 00:20:51,438
the way you score each one
of the individual instruments.

281
00:20:51,487 --> 00:20:54,320
Some bands have that sound already,
like Pollack,

282
00:20:54,367 --> 00:20:56,961
but it's not the right sound, not for me.

283
00:20:57,007 --> 00:20:59,840
- What is?
- I don't know.

284
00:20:59,887 --> 00:21:02,526
I don't know. I haven't found it yet.

285
00:21:02,567 --> 00:21:05,957
But someday I'm gonna find it
and when I do...

286
00:21:06,007 --> 00:21:08,282
You'll find it. I'm sure you will.

287
00:21:10,047 --> 00:21:12,607
- You are?
- Hey, Glenn!

288
00:21:14,087 --> 00:21:16,965
There's Chummy.
He found it all right. Goodbye.

289
00:21:17,007 --> 00:21:20,556
It's been wonderful seeing you. Goodbye.
I'm comin'!

290
00:21:20,607 --> 00:21:23,405
You'll be hearing from me. Wait and see.

291
00:21:26,647 --> 00:21:29,684
- Come on, boy, let's go.
- All right, all right.

292
00:21:33,047 --> 00:21:34,275
Bye.

293
00:21:42,847 --> 00:21:44,439
Honestly.

294
00:21:52,207 --> 00:21:55,040
(# Mellow version of Good Night Ladies)

295
00:22:15,927 --> 00:22:17,997
How about one more?
One more number?

296
00:22:18,047 --> 00:22:21,244
We can't, kids.
We're leaving for Atlantic City.

297
00:22:21,287 --> 00:22:23,323
We'll be back in a couple of months.

298
00:22:23,367 --> 00:22:25,198
Thanks a lot. Swell.

299
00:22:25,247 --> 00:22:28,717
Fellas, listen just a minute
before you start packing up.

300
00:22:28,767 --> 00:22:33,557
The bus leaves from the hotel for
Atlantic City tomorrow morning at 10:30.

301
00:22:33,607 --> 00:22:37,998
Everybody be on time.
Don't be late, will ya? OK.

302
00:22:39,287 --> 00:22:42,882
Ben, like I told you,

303
00:22:42,927 --> 00:22:45,487
I guess this is where I get off.

304
00:22:45,527 --> 00:22:47,722
I want to thank you for everything.

305
00:22:47,767 --> 00:22:49,962
- You know what you're doin'?
- Yeah.

306
00:22:50,007 --> 00:22:54,080
I wanna stick around New York for a while.
I want to do some studying.

307
00:22:54,127 --> 00:22:57,278
Just when the band's
really startin' to take on.

308
00:22:57,327 --> 00:23:00,717
I know all that. I appreciate
everything you've done for me

309
00:23:00,767 --> 00:23:03,645
and I wish you all the luck in the world.

310
00:23:03,687 --> 00:23:09,364
If there's... Any time you want me to do
an arrangement for you, just let me know.

311
00:23:09,407 --> 00:23:13,036
That's an idea.
Well, so long, kid. A lotta luck.

312
00:23:13,087 --> 00:23:15,442
- Thanks for everything.
- Goodbye.

313
00:23:15,487 --> 00:23:18,081
- You're really serious about this?
- Yeah.

314
00:23:18,127 --> 00:23:21,437
Still got that crazy idea in your head,
that sound?

315
00:23:23,327 --> 00:23:25,636
Hey, Don?

316
00:23:25,687 --> 00:23:28,281
This is Chummy MacGregor.
This is Don Haynes.

317
00:23:28,327 --> 00:23:31,205
- Hi.
- Glad to meet ya. You're the band booker.

318
00:23:31,247 --> 00:23:33,556
Gonna try and get Glenn
some work arranging.

319
00:23:33,607 --> 00:23:35,837
- It's an awful lonely town.
- I know.

320
00:23:35,887 --> 00:23:39,846
I wish we could stick together,
but I've been eating for two years now.

321
00:23:39,887 --> 00:23:42,720
It's gotten to be a habit.
I don't think I can break it.

322
00:23:42,767 --> 00:23:44,837
I know.

323
00:23:44,887 --> 00:23:48,038
Well, good luck, kid.
Hope you find a friendly pawn shop.

324
00:23:48,087 --> 00:23:50,282
- Yeah, bye, Chummy.
- So long.

325
00:24:40,487 --> 00:24:43,126
- Glenn!
- Hi, Don. How are you?

326
00:24:43,167 --> 00:24:45,044
- What are you doin'?
- Not much.

327
00:24:45,087 --> 00:24:49,922
Listen, Red Nichols is getting together
a pit band for a new musical, Girl Crazy.

328
00:24:49,967 --> 00:24:52,879
I know you're still looking for
that sound but it's been two years.

329
00:24:52,927 --> 00:24:56,044
- You won't find it on an empty stomach.
- I sure can't.

330
00:24:56,087 --> 00:24:59,477
A lot of your friends are in the band -
Benny Goodman, Babe Russin.

331
00:24:59,527 --> 00:25:03,645
- It's a great chance. It'll run all season.
- I guess I better take it.

332
00:25:03,687 --> 00:25:05,882
I'll call you tomorrow. I gotta run.

333
00:25:05,927 --> 00:25:07,918
Thanks a lot.

