Helen?

471
00:39:21,967 --> 00:39:25,562
- Good morning.
- Honey, what are you doing up at this hour?

472
00:39:25,607 --> 00:39:28,405
This hour? I've been up since seven.

473
00:39:28,447 --> 00:39:31,200
Well, come here.

474
00:39:31,247 --> 00:39:33,556
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

475
00:39:41,647 --> 00:39:44,400
7:00? It must be dark outside.

476
00:39:44,447 --> 00:39:48,520
No, it is not.
I've been getting up at this hour all of my life.

477
00:39:48,567 --> 00:39:52,037
But you haven't been staying up
until 4:00 in the morning.

478
00:39:52,087 --> 00:39:54,647
Well, no, that's true.
Only when you were around.

479
00:39:54,687 --> 00:39:58,646
That's right.
Your father on the porch with his shotgun.

480
00:40:04,327 --> 00:40:06,966
- What have you been doing?
- The ironing.

481
00:40:07,727 --> 00:40:11,117
The ironing? Honey, this is a hotel.

482
00:40:11,167 --> 00:40:14,682
All you have to do is pick up the phone.
They have people to do that.

483
00:40:14,727 --> 00:40:17,082
- But did you see what they charge?
- No.

484
00:40:17,127 --> 00:40:19,163
- It's just terrible.
- Is that so?

485
00:40:19,207 --> 00:40:22,005
I don't think we should
waste our money like that.

486
00:40:22,047 --> 00:40:25,722
- Nobody can say I married a spendthrift.
- No, sir.

487
00:40:25,767 --> 00:40:28,076
I'm a penny-pinching miser.

488
00:40:31,687 --> 00:40:35,885
I'm the kind of wife that steals money
out of your pockets and puts it in the bank.

489
00:40:35,927 --> 00:40:39,715
- Would you really do that?
- Sure. I've already started.

490
00:40:48,967 --> 00:40:51,162
(# Can Can building to crescendo)

491
00:40:57,887 --> 00:40:59,957
(Applause)

492
00:41:13,647 --> 00:41:15,205
- Hi, dear.
- Hi.

493
00:41:15,247 --> 00:41:19,365
It's a long movie. We have
two hours before the next stage show.

494
00:41:19,407 --> 00:41:22,558
- Have a good time?
- I like the show. But the music!

495
00:41:22,607 --> 00:41:24,802
Well, you know the music.

496
00:41:24,847 --> 00:41:29,079
- That isn't the way you want to play, is it?
- No, but I like pit work.

497
00:41:29,127 --> 00:41:32,085
It pays well. You get to stay in one place.

498
00:41:32,127 --> 00:41:36,439
Glenn, I've been thinking.
How much does that Dr Schillinger charge?

499
00:41:36,487 --> 00:41:39,285
He's pretty expensive. I don't know exactly.

500
00:41:39,327 --> 00:41:41,318
I haven't worked with him for years.

501
00:41:41,367 --> 00:41:44,120
That's just exactly what I mean. Why not?

502
00:41:44,167 --> 00:41:45,998
I don't know. I...

503
00:41:46,047 --> 00:41:49,323
What happened to that dream of yours?
What about that sound?

504
00:41:49,367 --> 00:41:51,835
Well, I've been working on that, Helen.

505
00:41:51,887 --> 00:41:55,596
It's an uphill grind.
My chance will come one of these days.

506
00:41:56,847 --> 00:42:00,522
To tell you the truth, Glenn,
I've been sort of disappointed.

507
00:42:03,327 --> 00:42:05,397
You mean that?

508
00:42:09,767 --> 00:42:14,363
If I started to study again,
we'd have to make all sorts of sacrifices.

509
00:42:14,407 --> 00:42:16,443
I'd have to give up those record dates.

510
00:42:17,367 --> 00:42:20,882
Darling, I don't want to live in a fancy hotel.

511
00:42:20,927 --> 00:42:24,078
We could get an awfully cute
little apartment.

512
00:42:24,127 --> 00:42:26,641
I just want you to keep on trying.

513
00:42:29,847 --> 00:42:31,838
I've sort of let you down, haven't I?

514
00:42:34,247 --> 00:42:35,919
A little.

515
00:42:37,887 --> 00:42:39,878
I'm sorry, Helen.

516
00:42:42,287 --> 00:42:46,724
You're right. I should start to study again. I...

517
00:42:46,767 --> 00:42:50,362
Why don't I call Schillinger right now?
See if he'll take me back.

518
00:42:50,407 --> 00:42:52,318
I have his phone number here...

519
00:42:52,367 --> 00:42:55,245
It's Trafalgar 7-5-0-9-8.

520
00:42:55,287 --> 00:42:57,517
- 7-5-0-9...
- Eight.

521
00:42:57,567 --> 00:43:00,286
Well... Well...

522
00:43:02,927 --> 00:43:04,724
7-5-0-9-8.

523
00:43:04,767 --> 00:43:09,079
(# Playing romantic tune)

524
00:43:23,487 --> 00:43:24,920
- Helen?
- Yes?

525
00:43:24,967 --> 00:43:29,324
- Where are my glasses?
- Right here! Why don't you put them on?

526
00:43:29,367 --> 00:43:32,120
I'll have to get some glasses
to find my glasses.

527
00:43:32,167 --> 00:43:34,078
What were you playing? It's lovely.

528
00:43:34,127 --> 00:43:37,961
A little exercise I'm working out
for Schillinger. I hope he likes it.

529
00:43:38,007 --> 00:43:40,202
Does that mean you won't be able to use it?

530
00:43:40,247 --> 00:43:44,160
No, that doesn't make any difference.
It's not that good, though.

531
00:43:44,207 --> 00:43:45,799
I think it is.

532
00:43:45,847 --> 00:43:48,759
- You like it as good as Little Brown Jug?
- No.

533
00:43:48,807 --> 00:43:51,037
But I think you should do something with it.

534
00:43:51,087 --> 00:43:54,966
I suppose you could make a song out of it.
Get somebody to write lyrics.

535
00:43:55,007 --> 00:43:58,158
Have to get a title. What's a good title?

536
00:43:58,207 --> 00:44:03,235
Well, it should be soft and romantic.
Sort of like moonlight.

537
00:44:03,287 --> 00:44:07,246
Moonlight. Young lover
under his sweetheart's window.

538
00:44:07,287 --> 00:44:10,882
You wouldn't be thinking
of a certain night in Boulder?

539
00:44:10,927 --> 00:44:13,600
There wasn't any moonlight. Just a shotgun!

540
00:44:13,647 --> 00:44:16,115
I know. And you didn't serenade me either.

541
00:44:16,167 --> 00:44:19,079
I didn't have a chance.
Serenade. There's a title.

542
00:44:19,127 --> 00:44:23,200
- Serenade in the Moonlight.
- How about Moonlight Serenade?

543
00:44:23,247 --> 00:44:25,317
Moonlight Serenade? Not bad.

544
00:44:25,367 --> 00:44:27,881
- It's kinda pretty.
- Moonlight Serenade.

545
00:44:27,927 --> 00:44:31,397
(Up-tempo) # I stand at your gate

546
00:44:31,447 --> 00:44:35,201
# And the song that I sing is of moonlight

547
00:44:35,247 --> 00:44:38,557
# I stand and I wait

548
00:44:38,607 --> 00:44:42,566
# For the touch of your hand
in the June night

549
00:44:42,607 --> 00:44:45,917
# The roses are sighin'

550
00:44:45,967 --> 00:44:49,960
# A moonlight serenade

551
00:44:50,007 --> 00:44:53,079
# Let us stray till the break of day

552
00:44:53,127 --> 00:44:56,676
# In love's valley of dreams

553
00:44:56,727 --> 00:44:58,683
# Just you and I

554
00:44:58,727 --> 00:45:00,718
# The summer sky

555
00:45:00,767 --> 00:45:03,804
# A heavenly breeze kissing the trees

556
00:45:03,847 --> 00:45:07,522
# So don't let me wait

557
00:45:07,567 --> 00:45:11,116
# Come to me tenderly in the June night

558
00:45:11,167 --> 00:45:14,603
# I stand at your gate

559
00:45:14,647 --> 00:45:18,401
# And I sing you a song in the moonlight

560
00:45:18,447 --> 00:45:21,996
# A love song, my darling

561
00:45:22,047 --> 00:45:29,123
# A moonlight serenade #

562
00:45:30,087 --> 00:45:31,725
(Scattered applause)

563
00:45:35,127 --> 00:45:38,358
- What have they done to my tune?
- It wasn't very good.

564
00:45:38,407 --> 00:45:42,525
The song is supposed to be a ballad,
not a hootchy-kootchy dance!

565
00:45:42,567 --> 00:45:47,322
They made a production number out of it.
And that arrangement, Holy Moses!

566
00:45:47,367 --> 00:45:49,039
Why wouldn't he use yours?

567
00:45:49,087 --> 00:45:51,521
Every band leader
wants his own arrangement.

568
00:45:51,567 --> 00:45:55,162
So do you! If you had your own band,
this sort of thing wouldn't happen.

569
00:45:55,207 --> 00:45:58,279
- Of course.
- Let's go. We have a lot to do.

570
00:45:59,687 --> 00:46:02,884
We need an instrument truck, and a car.

571
00:46:02,927 --> 00:46:05,600
That's two down payments.
If we use Chummy's car...

572
00:46:05,647 --> 00:46:08,684
Wait till you see what I got now.
Snappiest job on the road.

573
00:46:08,727 --> 00:46:12,640
It's a big Phaeton. Even got
a separate windshield for the back seat.

574
00:46:12,687 --> 00:46:15,326
You can always be
the first one to arrive in town.

575
00:46:15,367 --> 00:46:17,756
We'll need music stands and a copyist.

576
00:46:17,807 --> 00:46:22,835
We can do the copying. Like the old days,
no food but plenty of manuscript paper.

577
00:46:22,887 --> 00:46:24,559
What do you mean, no food?

578
00:46:24,607 --> 00:46:28,043
- We'll need at least 1,800.
- Then we're all set.

579
00:46:28,087 --> 00:46:31,397
Honey, he means we need $1,800
to start the band.

580
00:46:31,447 --> 00:46:33,438
Yes.

581
00:46:35,167 --> 00:46:38,637
- We don't need anything but good luck.
- What's this?

582
00:46:38,687 --> 00:46:40,882
"The Glenn Miller Band Account"?

583
00:46:45,367 --> 00:46:47,562
$1,842!

584
00:46:51,007 --> 00:46:53,077
Now eat your dinner.

585
00:46:58,247 --> 00:47:01,922
Hey. Did you get all that money
out of my pockets?

586
00:47:01,967 --> 00:47:03,878
Mm-hm.

587
00:47:06,087 --> 00:47:08,806
(# Upbeat swing)

588
00:47:23,367 --> 00:47:26,165
We're late for the job now.
I better go on ahead.

589
00:47:26,207 --> 00:47:30,325
- You fellas get there as quick as you can.
- All right, Glenn.

590
00:47:30,367 --> 00:47:32,278
Practically a new tyre too.

591
00:47:33,247 --> 00:47:36,444
(# Somewhere Over The Rainbow)

592
00:48:27,727 --> 00:48:29,957
Helen, you don't look very well.

593
00:48:30,007 --> 00:48:33,602
I'm just fine. I'm just a little tired.

594
00:48:33,647 --> 00:48:36,957
And poor Glenn is up all night
working on the arrangements

595
00:48:37,007 --> 00:48:39,680
and I have to sort of
take care of the bookkeeping.

596
00:48:39,727 --> 00:48:44,243
Has the business manager
given you the big financial statement yet?

597
00:48:44,287 --> 00:48:48,724
No, but I will. We left New York
with $42 in the bank.

598
00:48:48,767 --> 00:48:51,884
After six months,
we've paid for the truck and the car.

599
00:48:51,927 --> 00:48:54,441
That leaves a balance of 48.

600
00:48:54,487 --> 00:48:57,797
In short, we're making exactly $1 a month.

601
00:48:57,847 --> 00:48:59,997
So in ten years we'll have made $120.

602
00:49:00,047 --> 00:49:02,481
It takes time for a new band to catch on.

603
00:49:03,727 --> 00:49:05,285
It sure does.

604
00:49:05,327 --> 00:49:08,364
I don't know.
One night we pack 'em in and they love us.

605
00:49:08,407 --> 00:49:10,557
The next six dates we die.

606
00:49:10,607 --> 00:49:13,724
We don't seem to be getting anywhere,
and we don't deserve to!

607
00:49:13,767 --> 00:49:17,965
I just haven't been able to hit
the right combination.

608
00:49:18,007 --> 00:49:21,886
I just still haven't got that sound.

609
00:49:22,407 --> 00:49:25,604
Glenn, maybe if you stop playing.

610
00:49:26,687 --> 00:49:29,201
- Touché!
- I'm sorry. I didn't mean...

611
00:49:29,247 --> 00:49:32,717
I know what you mean.
Get a baton and start leading. No.

612
00:49:32,767 --> 00:49:36,442
Once you step out in front of the boys,
you can never be a sideman again.

613
00:49:36,487 --> 00:49:38,478
I'll stick to my trombone.

614
00:49:38,527 --> 00:49:40,643
I've got some good news for a change.

615
00:49:40,687 --> 00:49:44,726
I talked to Si Schribman.
He runs the State Ballroom in Boston.

616
00:49:44,767 --> 00:49:46,883
He's booked you in
for the week of the 22nd.

617
00:49:46,927 --> 00:49:49,760
That means six half-hour air spots.
That's what counts.

618
00:49:49,807 --> 00:49:53,766
- It sure does!
- Imagine! A whole week in one town.

619
00:49:53,807 --> 00:49:56,401
I could even get the washing
and the mending done.

620
00:49:56,447 --> 00:49:59,484
- Let's all drink to Boston!
- I think we should.

621
00:49:59,527 --> 00:50:01,438
Good ol' Boston.

622
00:50:07,887 --> 00:50:11,084
Glenn, why don't you ever use
Moonlight Serenade?

623
00:50:11,127 --> 00:50:14,403
Don't we have enough trouble
without resurrecting that?

624
00:50:14,447 --> 00:50:17,120
- Well, I liked it.
- So did I.

625
00:50:17,167 --> 00:50:20,159
That's two of us.
Now, if we can just find a third.

626
00:50:28,807 --> 00:50:32,322
- How's she look?
- Could be worse. Don't know how.

627
00:50:32,367 --> 00:50:34,961
You need a new axle housing,
an axle shaft,

628
00:50:35,007 --> 00:50:37,840
ring gear and pinion,
differential gear case.

629
00:50:37,887 --> 00:50:41,118
- How long'll it take?
- A few days once I get the parts.

630
00:50:41,167 --> 00:50:45,240
- You don't have 'em here?
- Don't have many calls for ring gears.

631
00:50:45,287 --> 00:50:49,075
Might have to go to Woodstock
soon as it stops snowing.

632
00:50:49,127 --> 00:50:51,038
- It could be worse.
- Yeah.

633
00:50:51,847 --> 00:50:54,315
There's Helen.
Get a hold of Schribman?

634
00:50:54,367 --> 00:50:58,280
No, I couldn't get Boston.
The telephone lines are down.

635
00:50:58,327 --> 00:51:01,160
Chummy, you and Helen
better try and make Boston.

636
00:51:01,207 --> 00:51:03,596
Tell Schribman we'll be there
as soon as we can.

637
00:51:03,647 --> 00:51:06,525
He's probably guessed what happened.

638
00:51:06,567 --> 00:51:10,037
- He wouldn't cancel on us.
- No, we'll get there all right.

639
00:51:10,087 --> 00:51:13,204
We can't lose that week in Boston.
Go ahead. Bye, dear.

640
00:51:13,247 --> 00:51:15,124
- Take care.
- Yeah.

641
00:51:29,287 --> 00:51:31,403
- You Mr Miller?
- Yeah.

642
00:51:31,447 --> 00:51:35,520
Man left a message. Your wife's sick.
They got her to the hospital.

643
00:51:35,567 --> 00:51:37,956
- What hospital?
- Boston Memorial.

644
00:51:42,327 --> 00:51:44,283
Mr Miller, she's a very sick girl.

645
00:51:44,327 --> 00:51:47,842
We gave her a transfusion
but we're lucky this happened when it did.

646
00:51:47,887 --> 00:51:51,880
A few months further along and we might've
lost the mother as well as the child.

647
00:51:51,927 --> 00:51:53,997
I had no idea that she was...

648
00:51:54,047 --> 00:51:56,083
- All right, Doctor.
- Thank you.

649
00:51:56,127 --> 00:51:58,118
Just for a minute.

650
00:52:12,847 --> 00:52:14,917
Helen.

651
00:52:19,247 --> 00:52:21,238
The truck all right?

652
00:52:27,527 --> 00:52:31,315
Five and a quarter, cash on the barrel head.
Take it or leave it, boys.

653
00:52:31,367 --> 00:52:33,358
Better than the others.

654
00:52:33,407 --> 00:52:35,602
I guess we'll have to take it.

655
00:52:35,647 --> 00:52:39,401
Kinda leaves us in a spot.
It's $900 to pay the boys in the band.

656
00:52:39,447 --> 00:52:41,438
With my car? How much'll you give us?

657
00:52:41,487 --> 00:52:44,445
- You're not gonna do it.
- I can sell my own car if I want to.

658
00:52:44,487 --> 00:52:48,526
Four hundred. That makes
nine and a quarter for all three of 'em.

659
00:52:48,567 --> 00:52:52,560
- This isn't your problem.
- Why isn't it? I wanna get paid off, too.

660
00:52:52,607 --> 00:52:54,723
You got a deal. Just one condition.

661
00:52:54,767 --> 00:52:57,759
I need the car long enough
to drive the boys to the station.

662
00:52:57,807 --> 00:52:59,399
Yes, that can be arranged.

663
00:52:59,447 --> 00:53:02,359
Fellas, pile in. I'll drive you to the station.

664
00:53:02,407 --> 00:53:04,398
Thank you, Chummy.

665
00:53:08,927 --> 00:53:11,760
- Hi, dear. How do you feel?
- Fine.

666
00:53:11,807 --> 00:53:14,241
- You look much better.
- Good.

667
00:53:14,287 --> 00:53:17,279
The doctor said if I behave myself,
I'll be up in a few days.

668
00:53:17,327 --> 00:53:19,079
Good.

669
00:53:19,127 --> 00:53:22,005
I've made up my mind
about something, young lady.

670
00:53:22,047 --> 00:53:24,845
If I ever go on the road again,

671
00:53:24,887 --> 00:53:29,199
you're gonna stay in that nice apartment
of ours on East 57th Street.

672
00:53:29,247 --> 00:53:31,283
You just listen to me, Glenn Miller.

673
00:53:31,327 --> 00:53:34,319
You enticed a little country girl
to run away and marry you

674
00:53:34,367 --> 00:53:36,005
and now you're hooked with her.

675
00:53:36,047 --> 00:53:39,801
And I'm not gonna let you go
gallivanting around the country without me.

676
00:53:39,847 --> 00:53:43,044
You're hooked with
a no-good itinerant musician.

677
00:53:43,087 --> 00:53:47,000
- I'm not complaining.
- I know. You never do.

678
00:53:47,047 --> 00:53:50,676
But I know how you wanted kids.

679
00:53:50,727 --> 00:53:53,844
I want to tell you something else
I've made up my mind about.

680
00:53:53,887 --> 00:53:56,959
We're not gonna have just one child.
We're gonna have two!

681
00:53:57,007 --> 00:53:58,998
We're gonna have a boy and a girl.

682
00:53:59,047 --> 00:54:00,719
- Glenn, I can't.
- I know.

683
00:54:00,767 --> 00:54:03,076
The doctor told me, but I mean it.

684
00:54:03,127 --> 00:54:07,917
There'll be two kids meant for us.
Somewhere we're gonna find them.

685
00:54:10,487 --> 00:54:12,682
I hope so.

686
00:54:16,887 --> 00:54:18,957
Who sent these flowers?

687
00:54:19,007 --> 00:54:21,202
- The boys in the band.
- Wasn't that nice?

688
00:54:21,247 --> 00:54:23,158
They're sweet.

689
00:54:25,047 --> 00:54:26,924
What's happened? Any dates?

690
00:54:28,247 --> 00:54:30,477
No. No dates.

691
00:54:31,807 --> 00:54:33,718
There's no band.

692
00:54:33,767 --> 00:54:36,327
We had to sell the cars
and pay off the boys.

693
00:54:36,367 --> 00:54:40,155
Chummy had to sell his Phaeton.
Isn't that a shame?

694
00:54:40,207 --> 00:54:42,721
Poor Chummy really loved that car.

695
00:54:45,727 --> 00:54:48,799
Glenn, you had a good band.

696
00:54:48,847 --> 00:54:52,078
It was getting better all the time.
It wasn't your fault.

697
00:54:52,127 --> 00:54:54,357
It's my fault all right!

698
00:54:54,407 --> 00:54:57,205
I'm broke, I'm in debt,
I don't even have a job.

699
00:54:57,247 --> 00:55:02,037
I told you before, you've gotten mixed up
with a no-good itinerant musician.

700
00:55:02,087 --> 00:55:05,602
- And I love him.
- And I love you.

701
00:55:09,367 --> 00:55:11,278
It's almost worth it.

702
00:55:11,327 --> 00:55:15,798
It's the first time you've told me that
since the day we were married.

703
00:55:27,887 --> 00:55:29,923
Come in.

704
00:55:31,407 --> 00:55:34,046
- Mrs Miller?
- Yes.

705
00:55:34,087 --> 00:55:36,601
I thought so. I can come in?

706
00:55:36,647 --> 00:55:38,558
Well, yes, of course.

707
00:55:41,007 --> 00:55:43,316
I brought you some flowers.

708
00:55:43,367 --> 00:55:46,325
Oh. Well, thank you very much.

709
00:55:50,367 --> 00:55:53,200
- They're all right?
- They're lovely.

710
00:55:53,247 --> 00:55:57,081
I'm a bachelor, I got no wife
to tell me these things.

711
00:55:57,127 --> 00:55:59,925
- Well, they're very pretty.
- Yeah.

712
00:55:59,967 --> 00:56:02,959
I heard all about the band
and how you were sick.

713
00:56:03,007 --> 00:56:05,965
Such a shame. I can sit down a minute?

714
00:56:06,607 --> 00:56:08,359
Yes, please.

715
00:56:09,367 --> 00:56:11,835
"Compliments of the State Ballroom."

716
00:56:13,007 --> 00:56:16,682
- Is this a joke?
- I shoulda said so right away.

717
00:56:16,727 --> 00:56:19,195
No, that's me. Si Schribman.

718
00:56:19,247 --> 00:56:21,886
Si Schribman!
If I'd known who you were...

719
00:56:21,927 --> 00:56:25,476
I know. Don Haynes said you wanted
to give me a piece of your mind.

720
00:56:25,527 --> 00:56:27,438
That's why I came here.

721
00:56:27,487 --> 00:56:29,876
Maybe we can exchange pieces of mind.

722
00:56:31,087 --> 00:56:35,239
I'm not really such an ogre.
I didn't like cancelling you out.

723
00:56:35,287 --> 00:56:38,962
But an old widow lady, 75,
she owns that ballroom.

724
00:56:39,007 --> 00:56:41,237
If I don't have a band, I don't pay the rent.

725
00:56:41,287 --> 00:56:44,643
If I don't pay the rent,
that old lady don't eat.

726
00:56:44,687 --> 00:56:46,678
It's a bad situation.

727
00:56:47,647 --> 00:56:52,118
If she would only die, God forbid,
then I could run it like I like.

728
00:56:52,167 --> 00:56:54,840
- It finished us. You know that.
- Yeah.

729
00:56:54,887 --> 00:56:57,560
- We had to break up the band.
- I know.

730
00:56:57,607 --> 00:56:59,882
I heard the band. It was good.

731
00:56:59,927 --> 00:57:02,680
Not great, mind you, but good, very good.

732
00:57:02,727 --> 00:57:07,847
We were just getting started.
Well, now I don't know what we'll do.

733
00:57:07,887 --> 00:57:12,722
Just don't you worry, young lady.
Get well, and don't worry about the band.

734
00:57:13,647 --> 00:57:15,365
That's easy to say.

735
00:57:15,407 --> 00:57:18,205
I believe in Glenn
and I believe what he's trying to do,

736
00:57:18,247 --> 00:57:20,158
so naturally I worry.

737
00:57:20,927 --> 00:57:24,203
I tell you, you send him over,
he should see me.

738
00:57:24,247 --> 00:57:26,807
With my own money
that don't go to the widow,

739
00:57:26,847 --> 00:57:30,362
- I sometimes invest in bands.
- Do you mean that?

740
00:57:30,407 --> 00:57:33,604
Would I make myself
so much trouble if I didn't?

741
00:57:34,487 --> 00:57:37,479
But there's a problem. I know Glenn.

742
00:57:37,527 --> 00:57:40,360
He's down right now
and he won't accept help.

743
00:57:40,407 --> 00:57:43,240
I don't think he'd risk
somebody else's money.

744
00:57:43,287 --> 00:57:45,960
I never even met your husband
and I like him already.

745
00:57:46,007 --> 00:57:48,840
You just leave it to me.
I'll cook up something.

746
00:57:48,887 --> 00:57:51,162
Thank you very much for coming.

747
00:57:51,207 --> 00:57:53,357
And I'm sorry I was so ungracious.

748
00:57:53,407 --> 00:57:58,162
Who was ungracious? We got along fine
exchanging pieces of mind.

749
00:57:58,207 --> 00:58:00,277
- Goodbye.
- Bye.

750
00:58:05,487 --> 00:58:08,638
I know you don't want a band but I'm stuck.

751
00:58:08,687 --> 00:58:12,646
But this Charley Firman sneaks a band
right out from under my nose.

752
00:58:12,687 --> 00:58:16,999
- I don't have any men. No money.
- I'll give you the money. Here.

753
00:58:17,047 --> 00:58:20,926
Five hundred. Six hundred. A thousand.

754
00:58:20,967 --> 00:58:23,959
There. You got the money.
Now, go get the men.

755
00:58:24,007 --> 00:58:29,127
I've tried all sorts of combinations.
I never found out what I was looking for.

756
00:58:29,167 --> 00:58:33,399
If I start again, I've got to have
an entirely different kind of a band.

757
00:58:33,447 --> 00:58:36,280
Different tunes.
I wanna try something radical.

758
00:58:36,327 --> 00:58:39,603
Fine. Go get radical, but just get going!

759
00:58:39,647 --> 00:58:43,925
I gotta have something in here
making a noise the kids can dance to.

760
00:58:48,047 --> 00:58:49,275
OK.

761
00:58:52,807 --> 00:58:56,686
- Let's have the five saxes right in there.
- Five saxes?

762
00:58:56,727 --> 00:58:59,195
And the trombones over there.

763
00:58:59,247 --> 00:59:01,761
And the four trumpets right behind them.

764
00:59:01,807 --> 00:59:03,957
Four trombones and four trumpets!

765
00:59:04,007 --> 00:59:06,601
When they play,
what's gonna hold the roof on?

766
00:59:06,647 --> 00:59:08,717
Five saxes and a trumpet lead.

767
00:59:08,767 --> 00:59:11,645
Maybe it's good and maybe it ain't,
but it's radical.

768
00:59:11,687 --> 00:59:13,086
Let's try this.

769
00:59:13,127 --> 00:59:16,676
Remember this is a ballad,
so take it nice and easy, don't bruise it.

770
00:59:16,727 --> 00:59:20,640
Joe, you stand up so I can get a balance
between you and the saxophones.

771
00:59:20,687 --> 00:59:22,359
All right, here we go.

772
00:59:22,407 --> 00:59:23,886
One,

773
00:59:23,927 --> 00:59:25,565
two.

774
00:59:25,607 --> 00:59:28,679
(# Band plays ballad)

775
01:00:41,127 --> 01:00:42,958
What's the matter?

776
01:00:43,007 --> 01:00:45,646
- He cut his lip.
- Let's see.

777
01:00:45,687 --> 01:00:49,123
Oh, no. You really split it open.
You better have it looked at.

778
01:00:49,167 --> 01:00:52,523
- I'm sorry, Glenn.
- Go on, Joe. Take care of it.

779
01:00:52,567 --> 01:00:54,478
Oh, no.

780
01:00:55,847 --> 01:00:57,917
All right, take five, boys.

781
01:01:06,487 --> 01:01:08,842
- Is it bad?
- He'll be out for weeks.

782
01:01:08,887 --> 01:01:12,243
- You get more tough breaks...
- Just when you got a good sound.

783
01:01:12,287 --> 01:01:16,166
It isn't what I want
but if we could've worked on it...

784
01:01:16,207 --> 01:01:20,120
- You can't find another trumpet blower?
- Not with Joe's range.

785
01:01:20,167 --> 01:01:22,635
All the arrangements have a trumpet lead?

786
01:01:22,687 --> 01:01:25,520
He had to hurt his lip
the day before you open.

787
01:01:25,567 --> 01:01:27,922
What are we gonna do?
Postpone the opening?

788
01:01:27,967 --> 01:01:31,437
- Poor old widow lady.
- We're not gonna postpone anything.

789
01:01:31,487 --> 01:01:35,480
We'll open tomorrow if I have to stay up
all night and rewrite the arrangement.

790
01:01:35,527 --> 01:01:38,917
- You can't. It's impossible.
- Wait a minute!

791
01:01:38,967 --> 01:01:41,197
Just a minute. I have an idea.

792
01:01:41,247 --> 01:01:45,479
Willie Schwartz could play
those parts on clarinet. Why not?

793
01:01:45,527 --> 01:01:47,518
You see? Clarinet lead. Why not?

794
01:01:47,567 --> 01:01:50,479
Get me lots of manuscript paper.
Can I use your office?

795
01:01:50,527 --> 01:01:52,165
Sure.

796
01:01:52,207 --> 01:01:55,961
Clarinet lead. Why not?
And, Don, call Helen, tell her not to worry.

797
01:01:56,007 --> 01:01:58,805
Tell her I'll be here all night.
Clarinet lead.

798
01:01:58,847 --> 01:02:02,601
And I can harmonise it real tight,
all in the same octave.

799
01:02:06,927 --> 01:02:08,838
Four saxes and a clarinet.

800
01:02:10,607 --> 01:02:12,518
He better stay up all night.

801
01:03:15,127 --> 01:03:18,722
(# Moonlight Serenade)

802
01:04:27,607 --> 01:04:29,598
(# Clarinet solo)

803
01:05:02,727 --> 01:05:05,764
He looks like he's got it, maybe.
Listen to those kids!

804
01:05:05,807 --> 01:05:09,561
There's no maybe about it.
That's it, that's the sound.

805
01:05:38,567 --> 01:05:40,762
(# Mellow music)

806
01:06:06,487 --> 01:06:08,398
(Applause)

807
01:06:34,327 --> 01:06:35,726
Thank you.

808
01:06:37,247 --> 01:06:39,477
Here's a brand-new number by Jerry Gray.

809
01:06:39,527 --> 01:06:42,041
I hope you like it as much as we do.

810
01:06:43,687 --> 01:06:45,598
(# Upbeat tune)

811
01:07:15,967 --> 01:07:19,403
I, uh, bought you a present for your birthday.

812
01:07:19,447 --> 01:07:22,484
My birthday? That isn't till next November.

813
01:07:22,527 --> 01:07:24,597
This is for your last birthday.

814
01:07:27,527 --> 01:07:30,405
- Oh, Glenn!
- They're just real.

815
01:07:32,247 --> 01:07:34,238
Here, let me try 'em on for size.

816
01:07:35,087 --> 01:07:36,600
There.

817
01:07:37,887 --> 01:07:40,321
Hm. Not bad.

818
01:09:13,487 --> 01:09:15,876
I forgot to tell you the name of that tune.

819
01:09:15,927 --> 01:09:18,202
We call it String Of Pearls.

820
01:09:48,567 --> 01:09:50,398
- Hi, Mother, Dad!
- Hi, Glenn.

821
01:09:50,447 --> 01:09:52,836
You rested up ready for the big night?

822
01:09:52,887 --> 01:09:55,276
We've had a wonderful time
with little Stevie.

823
01:09:55,327 --> 01:09:57,363
- Quite a boy. Big for his age.
- Isn't he?

824
01:09:57,407 --> 01:10:00,683
I can't tell you how much
it's meant to us to have him.

825
01:10:00,727 --> 01:10:03,002
- Is everything all set?
- Yes, dear.

826
01:10:03,047 --> 01:10:06,039
- Did you get Helen out of the house?
- Oh, yes.

827
01:10:06,087 --> 01:10:09,159
- Where'd she go?
- I suppose she's shopping.

828
01:10:09,207 --> 01:10:12,040
A girl doesn't have
a tenth wedding anniversary every day!

829
01:10:12,087 --> 01:10:14,806
- You sure she doesn't suspect anything?
- Oh, no.

830
01:10:14,847 --> 01:10:17,884
- Is everything all set back here?
- Oh, yes.

831
01:10:20,167 --> 01:10:22,601
I think Helen'll get a big kick out of this.

832
01:10:22,647 --> 01:10:24,319
She certainly will, Glenn.

833
01:10:25,887 --> 01:10:28,879
I've been lookin' about.
Quite a place you got here.

834
01:10:28,927 --> 01:10:30,645
It's beautiful, Glenn.

835
01:10:30,687 --> 01:10:33,485
- Paid for, is it?
- Yes, it's paid for.

836
01:10:33,527 --> 01:10:38,601
- Must be doin' pretty well.
- We hear him every night on that radio!

837
01:10:38,647 --> 01:10:41,320
That's only 15 minutes.
Don't suppose it pays much.

838
01:10:41,367 --> 01:10:45,280
Then there's the records.
And he's playing at the Hotel Pennsylvania.

839
01:11:07,647 --> 01:11:10,878
How much do they pay
for playing on one of those records?

840
01:11:10,927 --> 01:11:14,078
- We get three cents a record.
- Three cents?

841
01:11:14,127 --> 01:11:16,482
Have to sell a heap of records
to make it worthwhile.

842
01:11:16,527 --> 01:11:18,119
But they do, dear!

843
01:11:18,167 --> 01:11:21,079
- Let's go see Stevie.
- No, Helen wants us to wait.

844
01:11:21,127 --> 01:11:24,278
Why? Come on.
Sure, we can go on up there.

845
01:11:24,327 --> 01:11:28,206
- Hi. Stevie and I have a surprise for you.
- You do?

846
01:11:28,247 --> 01:11:30,807
- Let's go up to the nursery.
- Come on.

847
01:11:32,207 --> 01:11:34,960
How many copies
of a record do they sell, son?

848
01:11:35,007 --> 01:11:38,556
Moonlight Serenade,
we sold about 800,000 copies.

849
01:11:40,927 --> 01:11:43,361
- Did you say 800,000?
- That's right.

850
01:11:47,087 --> 01:11:48,964
What's...

851
01:11:49,007 --> 01:11:51,123
Look what just arrived.

852
01:11:54,527 --> 01:11:57,087
This is Stevie's new baby sister.

853
01:11:57,127 --> 01:12:00,836
- Can I pick her up?
- I think so. She's your daughter.

854
01:12:00,887 --> 01:12:04,675
Well, well, well.

855
01:12:05,367 --> 01:12:10,157
So you're Jonnie Dee!
Look, she's beautiful! Isn't she?

856
01:12:10,207 --> 01:12:12,323
Look at those red cheeks.

857
01:12:12,367 --> 01:12:15,837
Stevie, look at your baby sister.
Isn't she beautiful?

858
01:12:15,887 --> 01:12:19,516
- You sure surprised him!
- I've been planning it for months.

859
01:12:19,567 --> 01:12:23,446
- I told 'em I just had to have her today.
- How old is she?

860
01:12:23,487 --> 01:12:26,081
- Six weeks today.
- Old lady.

861
01:12:26,127 --> 01:12:31,076
- She's a hungry old woman.
- This is gonna take some expert action.

862
01:12:31,127 --> 01:12:34,483
Her young father's gonna feed her.
Let's have the bottle.

863
01:12:35,167 --> 01:12:37,078
Here, now. Here we go.

864
01:12:37,127 --> 01:12:39,595
All right, Jonnie Dee. There we are.

865
01:12:39,647 --> 01:12:41,763
How's your appetite?

866
01:12:41,807 --> 01:12:44,162
There! Is this hot enough?

867
01:12:44,207 --> 01:12:48,041
That's a good girl. The kid's starved.

868
01:12:55,447 --> 01:12:58,564
- Helen, we'll be late for the theatre.
- Coming.

869
01:12:58,607 --> 01:13:01,485
- I'll get the car.
- All right, dear.

870
01:13:01,527 --> 01:13:07,045
Glenn, I've been figuring. 800,000 records
at three cents apiece, that's $24,000.

871
01:13:07,087 --> 01:13:09,726
- That's right.
- Just for one record?

872
01:13:09,767 --> 01:13:12,918
Well, you certainly are doing well at that!

873
01:13:12,967 --> 01:13:16,642
All right, boys, right over here.
You all set? All right.

874
01:13:17,647 --> 01:13:19,797
Helen, come on!

875
01:13:19,847 --> 01:13:21,963
I'm coming!

876
01:13:22,007 --> 01:13:25,556
(# Band plays Here Comes The Bride)

877
01:13:41,087 --> 01:13:43,078
(All) Congratulations!

878
01:13:46,367 --> 01:13:48,358
What a surprise!

879
01:13:49,807 --> 01:13:52,116
- Oh, Mother!
- Darling!

880
01:13:52,167 --> 01:13:54,840
Oh, I'm glad to see you!

881
01:13:54,887 --> 01:13:57,720
- Polly, Don. How are you?
- It's a wonderful surprise!

882
01:13:57,767 --> 01:14:00,679
- We sort of surprised each other.
- Yes, we did!

883
01:14:00,727 --> 01:14:02,683
I've got another surprise.

884
01:14:02,727 --> 01:14:06,436
The band has a number,
and that's exactly what it is, a number.

885
01:14:06,487 --> 01:14:08,682
This is based on a telephone number

886
01:14:08,727 --> 01:14:12,686
that was kind of important to you and me,
Helen, about ten years ago.

887
01:14:12,727 --> 01:14:14,638
Here we go. One. Two.

888
01:14:15,287 --> 01:14:17,198
(# Upbeat intro)

889
01:14:34,207 --> 01:14:36,243
Now, listen to this. Now, watch.

890
01:14:37,167 --> 01:14:38,316
(Ringing)

891
01:14:38,367 --> 01:14:41,086
Pennsylvania 6-5000!

892
01:14:41,767 --> 01:14:44,235
- Remember?
- Yes!

893
01:14:50,727 --> 01:14:52,160
(Ringing)

894
01:14:52,207 --> 01:14:54,562
Pennsylvania 6-5000!

895
01:14:55,327 --> 01:14:58,364
Would you like to make this
a really memorable evening?

896
01:14:58,407 --> 01:15:00,921
- Dance with me.
- In front of all these people?

897
01:15:00,967 --> 01:15:04,277
In all the years we've been married
you've never danced with me.

898
01:15:04,327 --> 01:15:07,478
- And I may never get another chance.
- Here we go.

899
01:15:16,687 --> 01:15:18,837
- Now.
- (Ringing)

900
01:15:18,887 --> 01:15:21,640
- Pennsylvania 6-5000!
- Good.

901
01:15:27,287 --> 01:15:28,561
- Hi, Joe.
- Hi, Glenn.

902
01:15:28,607 --> 01:15:29,926
Glad to see ya.

903
01:15:29,967 --> 01:15:31,878
That's good.

904
01:15:37,207 --> 01:15:40,358
Come on, don't stand around.
Come on! Dance it up!

905
01:15:46,607 --> 01:15:48,723
Come on, let's try something.

906
01:16:01,007 --> 01:16:04,443
- That's pretty good. Let's try that again.
- All right.

907
01:16:09,407 --> 01:16:11,967
I think I better go back to the trombone.

908
01:16:15,007 --> 01:16:16,918
You sit down there.

909
01:16:29,847 --> 01:16:31,280
All right, you.

910
01:16:31,327 --> 01:16:34,717
- (Ringing)
- Pennsylvania 6-5-0-0-0!

911
01:17:17,967 --> 01:17:20,686
I'm kinda glad you called me that night.

912
01:17:20,727 --> 01:17:23,799
So am I.
All right, let's have something to eat.

913
01:17:23,847 --> 01:17:26,122
Come on. Come on, dear.

914
01:17:26,167 --> 01:17:28,840
- We're cutting a record of that.
- A record?

915
01:17:28,887 --> 01:17:30,525
- Three cents?
- Right.

916
01:17:30,567 --> 01:17:32,125
That's my boy!

917
01:17:34,527 --> 01:17:36,836
You oughta use that number in your picture.

918
01:17:36,887 --> 01:17:38,206
Picture?

919
01:17:38,247 --> 01:17:41,080
Glenn and the boys
are gonna do a movie in the fall.

920
01:17:41,127 --> 01:17:43,516
- Are you gonna be a movie star?
- Yes, Mother.

921
01:17:43,567 --> 01:17:47,879
I'm gonna play Tarzan and
swing from the trees playing my trombone.

922
01:17:48,407 --> 01:17:50,398
I'd like to propose a toast.

923
01:17:50,447 --> 01:17:53,120
To Glenn and Helen,
who serve the best food in town.

924
01:17:53,167 --> 01:17:57,445
Besides, the price is right.
We can remember when it wasn't like this.

925
01:17:57,487 --> 01:18:01,526
May you be as happy together always
as you are tonight.

926
01:18:05,447 --> 01:18:08,041
Thank you, Chummy.
That was a very nice speech.

927
01:18:08,687 --> 01:18:10,643
It oughta be, I worked on it all day!

928
01:18:10,687 --> 01:18:12,803
- You did?
- (Laughter)

929
01:18:12,847 --> 01:18:18,683
I thought your special number was gonna be
Helen's favourite, Little Brown Jug.

930
01:18:18,727 --> 01:18:20,319
He'd never do that. He hates it.

931
01:18:21,327 --> 01:18:24,399
I knew this would come up sooner or later.

932
01:18:24,447 --> 01:18:27,120
So I have an anniversary present
for my good wife

933
01:18:27,167 --> 01:18:29,123
and on the card it says,

934
01:18:29,167 --> 01:18:31,840
"Ha-ha-ha, you and me

935
01:18:31,887 --> 01:18:34,447
"We hardly ever disagree

936
01:18:34,487 --> 01:18:37,399
"So here you are, this will be

937
01:18:37,447 --> 01:18:40,757
"The one brown jug you'll get from me."

938
01:18:45,567 --> 01:18:48,639
- Roll 'em for a take.
- M3-45, take one.

939
01:18:49,647 --> 01:18:51,399
Here we go.

940
01:18:52,207 --> 01:18:55,563
One, two, three, four.

941
01:18:55,607 --> 01:18:57,723
(# Tuxedo Junction)

942
01:21:21,367 --> 01:21:23,358
All right. Save it.

943
01:21:29,407 --> 01:21:31,637
- Hello, everybody.
- Hi, Helen.

944
01:21:31,687 --> 01:21:33,598
Well, hi, dear.

945
01:21:33,647 --> 01:21:35,956
- I thought you'd like lunch.
- I sure would.

946
01:21:36,007 --> 01:21:37,804
I brought the mail.

947
01:21:45,167 --> 01:21:49,160
Chummy, we still have a little time.
Why don't you go over At Last?

948
01:21:49,207 --> 01:21:51,118
Let's go up to the control booth.

949
01:21:51,167 --> 01:21:53,362
- Anything wrong?
- No, no.

950
01:21:56,847 --> 01:21:58,758
Come on, sit down, honey.

951
01:21:58,807 --> 01:22:01,879
Helen, I wanted to talk to you about...

952
01:22:01,927 --> 01:22:05,806
With this picture deal
and the record sales and everything,

953
01:22:05,847 --> 01:22:08,361
- we're pretty well fixed.
- Yes.

954
01:22:08,407 --> 01:22:12,116
And, no matter what happens,
you and the kids,

955
01:22:12,167 --> 01:22:15,443
- you're in good shape.
- Yes, I know.

956
01:22:15,487 --> 01:22:17,637
Can you come to Men's Wardrobe at two?

957
01:22:17,687 --> 01:22:19,803
- Yeah.
- Thank you.

958
01:22:19,847 --> 01:22:22,281
So, I thought that...

959
01:22:23,207 --> 01:22:25,926
What I'm trying to get at...

960
01:22:25,967 --> 01:22:27,958
I've been thinking... Yeah?

961
01:22:28,007 --> 01:22:30,805
On Tuxedo Junction,
we'll have a wax right after lunch.

962
01:22:30,847 --> 01:22:32,883
Fine. Thanks very much.

963
01:22:33,887 --> 01:22:37,846
- So...
- Open the letter from the War Department.

964
01:22:37,887 --> 01:22:41,562
- I'm sure it's your commission.
- How do you know?

965
01:22:41,607 --> 01:22:45,600
I've known it for months.
I knew it was only a question of time.

966
01:22:45,647 --> 01:22:50,277
I just put in for it two weeks ago.
I guess you found out about it before I did.

967
01:22:50,327 --> 01:22:53,399
Go on, open it.
I want to know what to call you.

968
01:22:53,447 --> 01:22:55,358
Let's see.

969
01:22:58,487 --> 01:23:00,603
This is it all right.

970
01:23:00,647 --> 01:23:03,844
Captain. Captain Alton G Miller.

971
01:23:03,887 --> 01:23:08,039
Serial number 0-4-5-0-5-2-7-3.

972
01:23:09,927 --> 01:23:12,964
How soon will you be leaving,
Captain Miller?

973
01:23:13,527 --> 01:23:15,882
I don't know. It usually takes about a month.

974
01:23:15,927 --> 01:23:18,395
Don wants to go with me,
so do some of the boys.

975
01:23:18,447 --> 01:23:21,439
- Are you gonna have your own band?
- I hope so.

976
01:23:21,487 --> 01:23:25,685
You know, all the kids
that liked our music are in the service.

977
01:23:25,727 --> 01:23:28,241
- That's the reason I...
- I understand.

978
01:23:28,287 --> 01:23:30,881
I think you'll look very handsome in uniform.

979
01:23:30,927 --> 01:23:35,079
What do you think about it?
Are you upset?

980
01:23:35,127 --> 01:23:38,164
Of course I'm upset.
I don't want you to go

981
01:23:38,207 --> 01:23:42,041
but I guess I'd be
even more upset if you didn't.

982
01:23:45,247 --> 01:23:48,557
(# Marching music)

983
01:24:00,887 --> 01:24:04,562
- They sound good.
- Do we have to play this kind of music?

984
01:24:04,607 --> 01:24:07,201
We've marched to this music
for a hundred years.

985
01:24:07,247 --> 01:24:10,922
- That's what I mean.
- We're not gonna change now, Captain.

986
01:25:11,327 --> 01:25:14,444
We gotta do better
than this for General Arnold.

987
01:25:15,367 --> 01:25:17,642
(# Military drumming)

988
01:25:23,327 --> 01:25:25,841
(# Upbeat swing)

989
01:26:41,527 --> 01:26:43,358
In all my 27 years in the Army

990
01:26:43,407 --> 01:26:47,082
I have never witnessed a more
flagrant breach of military decorum.

991
01:26:47,127 --> 01:26:50,915
- Sorry, Colonel.
- And walking through a reviewing column!

992
01:26:50,967 --> 01:26:53,845
- I had to get to the band, sir.
- Then playing blues!

993
01:26:53,887 --> 01:26:58,165
You made a laughing stock of this entire
unit, and in front of General Arnold!

994
01:26:58,207 --> 01:27:00,926
- I had no such intentions.
- What was your intention?

995
01:27:00,967 --> 01:27:04,198
Blasting out right in the General's face!

996
01:27:04,247 --> 01:27:06,442
The men seemed tired, sir.

997
01:27:06,487 --> 01:27:09,763
- The men's condition is my responsibility.
- Yes, sir.

998
01:27:09,807 --> 01:27:13,277
I must warn you that your conduct calls
for disciplinary action.

999
01:27:13,327 --> 01:27:14,601
- Yes, sir.
- (Knock on door)

1000
01:27:14,647 --> 01:27:16,524
Come in.

1001
01:27:16,567 --> 01:27:20,242
Just wanted to say goodbye,
we're due in Washington tonight.

1002
01:27:20,287 --> 01:27:22,562
General Arnold, it's been a pleasure.

1003
01:27:22,607 --> 01:27:25,599
- I'm sorry that...
- Aren't you Captain Glenn Miller?

1004
01:27:25,647 --> 01:27:28,798
- Yes, sir.
- I want to congratulate you on your band.

1005
01:27:28,847 --> 01:27:32,237
- Thank you, sir.
- Great morale builder.

1006
01:27:32,287 --> 01:27:35,518
The effect was astonishing!
Keep up the good work.

1007
01:27:35,567 --> 01:27:38,035
- Yes, sir.
- I like your music myself.

1008
01:27:38,087 --> 01:27:39,884
Makes me think of home.

1009
01:27:39,927 --> 01:27:42,361
My children play your records day and night.

1010
01:27:42,407 --> 01:27:45,160
- May I make a suggestion, sir?
- Certainly.

1011
01:27:45,207 --> 01:27:49,200
I'd like to suggest that I be given
the authority to form my own band.

1012
01:27:49,247 --> 01:27:50,805
Play my kind of music.

1013
01:27:50,847 --> 01:27:52,838
Most of my men are in the service.

1014
01:27:52,887 --> 01:27:57,119
If we can be sent overseas,
I know we can be of value.

1015
01:27:57,167 --> 01:28:00,955
As you say, I think we can give the boys
a piece of home.

1016
01:28:01,007 --> 01:28:04,044
I must say I agree with you, Miller.

1017
01:28:04,087 --> 01:28:06,806
- I'll see what I can do.
- Thank you, sir.

1018
01:28:19,127 --> 01:28:20,958
Glenn!

1019
01:28:22,247 --> 01:28:24,397
Well, gee, I didn't expect this!

1020
01:28:24,447 --> 01:28:26,438
General Arnold brought us.

1021
01:28:26,487 --> 01:28:30,036
General, thank you.
I appreciate everything you've done.

1022
01:28:30,087 --> 01:28:33,966
A pleasure. I'll probably get court-martialled
but I brought 'em anyway.

1023
01:28:34,007 --> 01:28:35,679
- Good luck.
- Thank you.

1024
01:28:35,727 --> 01:28:38,002
- Goodbye and thank you.
- I enjoyed it.

1025
01:28:38,047 --> 01:28:40,163
- Goodbye, General.
- Goodbye.

1026
01:28:40,207 --> 01:28:42,437
Well, Jonnie Dee.

1027
01:28:42,487 --> 01:28:45,843
You got a hug for your daddy?
Got a hug for your daddy?

1028
01:28:45,887 --> 01:28:47,684
That's a girl!

1029
01:28:47,727 --> 01:28:50,799
How about you, young man?
How about you?

1030
01:28:50,847 --> 01:28:53,441
- Can I fly in your airplane?
- I'm afraid not.

1031
01:28:53,487 --> 01:28:55,876
You have to stay
and take care of your mother.

1032
01:28:55,927 --> 01:28:58,441
You be good
and don't cause him any trouble.

1033
01:28:58,487 --> 01:29:02,116
- I'll try not to. You take care of yourself.
- Don't worry.

1034
01:29:02,167 --> 01:29:05,239
You show 'em a picture of me
every once in a while.

1035
01:29:05,287 --> 01:29:08,199
I promise. And I'll read them your letters,
if you write.

1036
01:29:08,247 --> 01:29:09,999
I'm gonna write.

1037
01:29:10,047 --> 01:29:13,244
Gee, I'm gettin' homesick already.

1038
01:29:13,287 --> 01:29:17,724
It's funny how you can miss a person
even before he's gone.

1039
01:29:17,767 --> 01:29:19,678
Hurry it up, Glenn.

1040
01:29:20,487 --> 01:29:23,206
Goodbye, dear.
Goodbye, Stevie. Bye.

1041
01:30:05,767 --> 01:30:08,076
(Air-raid siren)

1042
01:30:30,127 --> 01:30:33,005
This is Glenn Miller
and the American Band of the AEF.

1043
01:30:33,047 --> 01:30:37,199
coming to you from Buzz Bomb Alley
through the courtesy of the BBC.

1044
01:30:37,247 --> 01:30:40,842
And to all you GI boys and girls
a long, long way from home,

1045
01:30:40,887 --> 01:30:44,960
and to all our British friends as well,
we hope to give you a little lift.

1046
01:30:45,007 --> 01:30:46,565
That's why we're here.

1047
01:30:46,607 --> 01:30:50,919
We'll start right out by seeing
if we can put you In The Mood.

1048
01:30:50,967 --> 01:30:53,527
(# Moonlight Serenade ends)

1049
01:31:00,687 --> 01:31:03,360
(# In The Mood)

1050
01:32:16,967 --> 01:32:19,037
(Air-raid siren)

1051
01:32:41,127 --> 01:32:43,516
(Air-raid siren continues)

1052
01:33:33,567 --> 01:33:35,285
(Explosion)

1053
01:34:03,287 --> 01:34:05,721
(Applause and whistling)

1054
01:34:10,527 --> 01:34:14,566
Thank you. A little while ago
an airplane landed out here

1055
01:34:14,607 --> 01:34:18,919
and out stepped a singing group
that you all know.

1056
01:34:18,967 --> 01:34:21,162
They sang with me back in the States.

1057
01:34:21,207 --> 01:34:24,358
Let's give 'em a good, warm welcome.
The Modernaires!

1058
01:34:24,407 --> 01:34:26,363
The Modernaires!

1059
01:34:31,727 --> 01:34:36,005
And somebody else stepped out of
that same airplane. A big surprise, boys.

1060
01:34:36,047 --> 01:34:38,117
Here's a girl you all know.

1061
01:34:38,167 --> 01:34:40,965
She's flown across the ocean
just to sing for you.

1062
01:34:41,007 --> 01:34:45,000
Let's give her a good, big ETO welcome.
Frances Langford!

1063
01:34:49,207 --> 01:34:50,799
Hi, Frances.

1064
01:34:55,527 --> 01:34:57,438
- Thank you, Glenn.
- Thank you.

1065
01:34:57,487 --> 01:35:00,160
- That's from Helen.
- Bless your heart.

1066
01:35:02,327 --> 01:35:07,276
I'll start out by taking you on a trip
south of the Mason-Dixon line.

1067
01:35:07,327 --> 01:35:10,717
Let's all get aboard
that old Chattanooga Choo Choo.

1068
01:36:04,207 --> 01:36:07,438
# Hi there, Fran, what you say?

1069
01:36:07,487 --> 01:36:11,082
# Step aside, partner, it's my day

1070
01:36:11,127 --> 01:36:14,756
# Lend an ear and listen to my version

1071
01:36:16,127 --> 01:36:22,043
# Of a really solid Tennessee excursion

1072
01:36:23,567 --> 01:36:27,560
# Pardon me, boy,
is this the Chattanooga Choo Choo?

1073
01:36:27,607 --> 01:36:29,040
# Yes, yes

1074
01:36:29,087 --> 01:36:30,998
# Track 29

1075
01:36:32,007 --> 01:36:34,521
# Boy, you can give me a shine

1076
01:36:36,527 --> 01:36:40,566
# I can afford
to board the Chattanooga Choo Choo

1077
01:36:40,607 --> 01:36:42,165
# Yes, yes

1078
01:36:42,207 --> 01:36:44,926
# I've got my fare

1079
01:36:44,967 --> 01:36:47,800
# And just a trifle to spare

1080
01:36:48,247 --> 01:36:52,718
# You leave the Pennsylvania Station
'bout a quarter to four

1081
01:36:52,767 --> 01:36:56,123
# Read a magazine
and then you're in Baltimore

1082
01:36:56,167 --> 01:36:59,284
# Dinner in the diner
# Nothing could be finer

1083
01:36:59,327 --> 01:37:02,842
# Than to have your ham and eggs
in Carolina

1084
01:37:02,887 --> 01:37:06,038
# When you hear the whistle blowin'
eight to the bar

1085
01:37:06,087 --> 01:37:09,443
# Then you know
that Tennessee is not very far

1086
01:37:09,487 --> 01:37:12,718
# Shovel all the coal in
# Gotta keep it rollin'

1087
01:37:12,767 --> 01:37:16,203
# Woo-woo, Chattanooga there you are

1088
01:37:19,167 --> 01:37:21,044
# There's gonna be

1089
01:37:21,087 --> 01:37:23,760
# A certain party at the station

1090
01:37:24,967 --> 01:37:27,003
# Waitin' for me

1091
01:37:27,487 --> 01:37:30,126
# How very happy we'll be

1092
01:37:31,847 --> 01:37:33,997
# He's gonna sigh

1093
01:37:34,047 --> 01:37:38,086
# Until I tell him that I'll never roam

1094
01:37:38,127 --> 01:37:42,086
# So, Chattanooga Choo Choo,
won't you choo-choo me home?

1095
01:37:42,127 --> 01:37:44,243
# Chattanooga, Chattanooga

1096
01:37:44,287 --> 01:37:47,245
# All aboard
# Chattanooga, Chattanooga

1097
01:37:47,607 --> 01:37:50,804
# All aboard
# Chattanooga, Chattanooga

1098
01:37:51,287 --> 01:37:58,967
# Chattanooga Choo Choo,
won't you choo-choo me home? #

1099
01:38:10,727 --> 01:38:13,082
(# Upbeat music)

1100
01:39:31,607 --> 01:39:34,758
- (# Music playing on radio)
- Remember that?

1101
01:39:34,807 --> 01:39:38,004
Seems a million years since we made that.

1102
01:39:38,047 --> 01:39:39,958
I wrote Glenn what you asked.

1103
01:39:40,887 --> 01:39:44,118
I want to read you his answer. He says...

1104
01:39:44,167 --> 01:39:46,237
"Tell Chummy not to take the job.

1105
01:39:46,287 --> 01:39:49,677
"As long as there's a Glenn Miller Band,
he'll be a part of it.

1106
01:39:49,727 --> 01:39:52,799
"Don and I have been making plans
for after the war.

1107
01:39:52,847 --> 01:39:55,236
"I have a lot of ideas for new arrangements,

1108
01:39:55,287 --> 01:39:58,597
"so tell Chummy to start looking
for a friendly pawn shop."

1109
01:39:58,647 --> 01:40:02,401
Friendly pawn shop.
He hasn't changed, has he?

1110
01:40:02,447 --> 01:40:06,201
Yes, he has! He's been promoted.
He's Major Glenn Miller now.

1111
01:40:06,247 --> 01:40:10,320
Major? That's wonderful.
I wish I could've gone with him.

1112
01:40:10,367 --> 01:40:14,485
You'd have made a fine soldier
with your heart and ulcers!

1113
01:40:14,527 --> 01:40:18,315
I've got two eyes and ten fingers.
That's all you need to play the piano.

1114
01:40:19,807 --> 01:40:22,321
They're going to Paris. I told you that.

1115
01:40:22,367 --> 01:40:26,076
And he says, "We're doing
a special programme on Christmas Day."

1116
01:40:26,127 --> 01:40:28,083
It's gonna be broadcast over here.

1117
01:40:28,127 --> 01:40:32,643
"Be sure and listen cos I'm sending you
an extra special Christmas present."

1118
01:40:32,687 --> 01:40:35,599
And I'll know what it is
if I listen to the programme.

1119
01:40:35,647 --> 01:40:39,959
- I wonder what he's gonna do.
- I don't know. But I'm sure gonna listen.

1120
01:40:59,687 --> 01:41:01,837
- Morning, Glenn.
- Morning, Colonel.

1121
01:41:01,887 --> 01:41:04,321
- I sure appreciate the lift.
- Not at all.

1122
01:41:04,367 --> 01:41:06,358
- You coming too?
- No. Tomorrow.

1123
01:41:06,407 --> 01:41:08,318
I got some work to do in Paris.

1124
01:41:08,367 --> 01:41:11,962
They're gonna let us do some shows
at the advance bases.

1125
01:41:12,007 --> 01:41:14,043
It's kinda soupy, isn't it?

1126
01:41:14,087 --> 01:41:17,363
It's always this way in December.
Shall we hop in?

1127
01:41:18,367 --> 01:41:21,996
Don, I don't know where I'll be,
so as soon as you land at Orly,

1128
01:41:22,047 --> 01:41:24,117
get in touch with the dispatcher.

1129
01:41:24,167 --> 01:41:26,635
Be sure the band goes over
that new arrangement.

1130
01:41:26,687 --> 01:41:29,679
- I want to use it.
- Right. See you tomorrow.

1131
01:41:29,727 --> 01:41:33,322
Pick up my mail.
I'm expecting a letter from Helen. Bye.

1132
01:42:03,047 --> 01:42:05,436
All right, hurry it up, you guys.

1133
01:42:05,487 --> 01:42:08,843
This is Paris. You wanted to see it.
Now's your chance.

1134
01:42:16,847 --> 01:42:21,443
I'm Lieutenant Haynes. Did Major
Glenn Miller leave a message here for me?

1135
01:42:21,487 --> 01:42:24,160
Nothing here, sir.
Did you try Flight Control?

1136
01:42:24,207 --> 01:42:29,042
No, he said he'd leave it here. He came
with Colonel Baessell on the Norseman.

1137
01:42:32,087 --> 01:42:33,884
The flight wasn't logged in.

1138
01:42:33,927 --> 01:42:37,124
No Norseman has landed here
in two or three days.

1139
01:42:37,167 --> 01:42:38,805
Thanks.

1140
01:42:45,487 --> 01:42:49,162
- General! I thought you were in Europe.
- Just arrived.

1141
01:42:49,207 --> 01:42:52,483
- May I congratulate you on your promotion?
- Thank you.

1142
01:42:52,527 --> 01:42:54,404
Five Star final.

1143
01:42:54,447 --> 01:42:56,597
Sounds like a late evening paper.

1144
01:42:58,247 --> 01:43:01,922
- Have you heard about Glenn Miller?
- Yes, this morning.

1145
01:43:01,967 --> 01:43:03,480
Notified his family yet?

1146
01:43:03,527 --> 01:43:07,042
We've been ordered to withhold notifications
until after Christmas.

1147
01:43:07,087 --> 01:43:11,797
His band is broadcasting tomorrow.
We can't let Mrs Miller find out that way.

1148
01:43:11,847 --> 01:43:15,203
- Do you mind if I call her personally?
- Of course not.

1149
01:43:15,247 --> 01:43:17,317
- Use my telephone.
- Thank you.

1150
01:43:24,167 --> 01:43:28,206
It's still a couple of minutes
before the broadcast, Helen.

1151
01:43:28,247 --> 01:43:32,160
You know, I never realised
how wonderful friends could be.

1152
01:43:32,207 --> 01:43:35,040
Even General Arnold, he called me himself.

1153
01:43:35,087 --> 01:43:39,319
That's why he's where he is, maybe,
because he's that kind of a guy.

1154
01:43:52,247 --> 01:43:55,125
Last night when I couldn't sleep,
I got to thinking.

1155
01:43:55,167 --> 01:43:57,078
It come to me about this broadcast.

1156
01:43:57,127 --> 01:43:59,960
You know, Helen, this is a test.

1157
01:44:00,727 --> 01:44:02,877
A test? How do you mean?

1158
01:44:02,927 --> 01:44:06,636
You remember how much we talked,
all of us,

1159
01:44:06,687 --> 01:44:11,078
about how Glenn's band
was something different?

1160
01:44:11,127 --> 01:44:14,881
Something permanent? An institution, like!

1161
01:44:16,367 --> 01:44:19,279
Yeah, Glenn and I talked about it often.

1162
01:44:19,327 --> 01:44:21,477
Don't you see what Si's getting at?

1163
01:44:21,527 --> 01:44:24,724
If the band goes on,
even if Glenn's not with it,

1164
01:44:24,767 --> 01:44:26,325
that's the proof.

1165
01:44:26,367 --> 01:44:30,326
It means that Glenn's band,
Glenn's music, keeps right on going,

1166
01:44:30,367 --> 01:44:34,838
and the kids'll be dancing to it
for years and years.

1167
01:44:34,887 --> 01:44:36,639
That's what he wanted.

1168
01:44:36,687 --> 01:44:40,123
(Announcer) 'We take you now to Paris
for a special programme.'

1169
01:44:40,167 --> 01:44:42,203
(# Moonlight Serenade)

1170
01:45:17,447 --> 01:45:22,043
'As some of you might know,
Major Glenn Miller is not with us today.

1171
